@node Volume Mounts
@section Volume Mounts

@opindex -v

@option{-v HOST:CONTAINER} bind-mounts a host path into the container.
The mount point is created inside the container if it does not exist.
The container path must be absolute and must not contain @code{..}.
May be repeated (up to 32).

@example
./alpine_latest -v /data:/data /bin/ls /data
./alpine_latest -v /data/input:/input -v /data/output:/output \
  /bin/sh -c 'cp /input/file /output/'
@end example

@node Secrets
@section Secrets

@opindex --secret

@option{--secret HOST_FILE[:CONTAINER_PATH]} bind-mounts a single host
file into the container read-only.  If @var{CONTAINER_PATH} is omitted,
the file lands at @file{/run/secrets/@var{basename}}.  Enforced with
@code{MS_RDONLY|MS_NOEXEC|MS_NOSUID|MS_NODEV}.  May be repeated.

@example
./my-app --secret ~/.config/api_key           # -> /run/secrets/api_key
./my-app --secret /etc/ssl/cert.pem:/certs/ca.pem
@end example

@node Environment Variables
@section Environment Variables

@opindex -e
@opindex --env-file

@option{-e KEY=VALUE} sets a variable inside the container.
@option{-e KEY} (no @code{=}) passes a variable from the host; if it is
not set on the host, a warning is printed and it is skipped.

@option{--env-file FILE} loads @code{KEY=VALUE} pairs from a file.
Blank lines and @code{#} comments are ignored.  @option{--env-file} and
@option{-e} are additive; files are processed before @option{-e} flags.

@example
./alpine_latest -e DEBUG=1 /bin/sh -c 'echo $DEBUG'
./my-app --env-file /etc/myapp.env -e OVERRIDE=1
@end example

@node Entrypoint and WorkingDir
@section Entrypoint and Working Directory

@opindex --entrypoint
@opindex --workdir

@option{--entrypoint PATH} overrides the image's OCI entrypoint.

@option{--workdir PATH} sets the working directory inside the container,
overriding the image's @code{WorkingDir}.  Defaults to @file{/} if
neither is set.

@example
./alpine_latest --entrypoint /bin/sh -c 'echo hello'
./my-app --workdir /app
@end example

@node User and Hostname
@section User and Hostname

@opindex --user
@opindex --hostname

@option{--user UID[:GID]} runs the container process as the given
numeric UID and optional GID.  Both values must be integers
@leq{}@tie{}65534.  @code{setgroups}, @code{setgid}, and @code{setuid}
are called; if any fail the container exits immediately.

@option{--hostname NAME} sets the hostname inside the UTS namespace.
Defaults to @code{oci2bin}.

@example
./my-app --user 1000:1000
./my-app --hostname mycontainer
@end example

@node Resource Limits
@section Resource Limits

@opindex --ulimit
@cindex ulimit
@cindex setrlimit

@option{--ulimit TYPE=N} sets resource limits via @code{setrlimit(2)}.
Both soft and hard limits are set to @var{N}.  May be repeated.

@multitable @columnfractions .2 .8
@headitem Type @tab Meaning
@item @code{nofile} @tab Maximum number of open file descriptors
@item @code{nproc}  @tab Maximum number of processes
@item @code{cpu}    @tab CPU time limit (seconds)
@item @code{as}     @tab Maximum virtual memory (bytes)
@item @code{fsize}  @tab Maximum file size (bytes)
@end multitable

@example
./my-app --ulimit nofile=1024 --ulimit nproc=64
./my-app --ulimit as=536870912     # 512 MiB virtual memory
@end example

@node SSH Agent Forwarding
@section SSH Agent Forwarding

@opindex --ssh-agent
@cindex SSH agent

@option{--ssh-agent} forwards the host @env{SSH_AUTH_SOCK} Unix socket
into the container at @file{/run/ssh-agent.sock} and sets
@env{SSH_AUTH_SOCK} accordingly.  The socket is bind-mounted read-only.
If @env{SSH_AUTH_SOCK} is unset or points to a non-socket, a warning is
printed and the container runs without agent forwarding.

@example
./my-app --ssh-agent /bin/sh -c 'ssh git@@github.com'
@end example

@node Extra tmpfs Mounts
@section Extra tmpfs Mounts

@opindex --tmpfs

@option{--tmpfs PATH} mounts a fresh in-memory filesystem at @var{PATH}
inside the container.  Useful for writable scratch space when
@option{--read-only} is active.  @var{PATH} must be absolute and must
not contain @code{..}.  May be repeated.

@example
./my-app --read-only --tmpfs /tmp --tmpfs /var/cache
@end example

@node Exposing Host Devices
@section Exposing Host Devices

@opindex --device

@option{--device /dev/HOST[:CONTAINER]} exposes a host device node
inside the container.  The host path must start with @file{/dev/}.  The
container path defaults to the host path if omitted.  @code{mknod(2)}
is attempted first; on failure a bind mount is used.  May be repeated.

@example
./my-app --device /dev/nvidia0         # GPU passthrough
./my-app --device /dev/ttyUSB0         # serial port
./my-app --device /dev/snd:/dev/snd    # audio
@end example

@node Exit Codes
@section Exit Codes

The container process exit status is forwarded to the caller.

@example
./alpine_latest /bin/sh -c 'exit 42'
echo $?   # prints 42
@end example

If the container process was killed by a signal, the exit status is 1.
Fatal setup errors (namespace creation, extraction failure) also exit
with status 1.

