@node Namespace Sharing
@chapter Sharing Namespaces Between Containers

@cindex namespace sharing
@cindex sidecar
@cindex IPC
@cindex network namespace
@opindex --net container
@opindex --ipc container

Two containers can share the same network or IPC namespace.  This
enables sidecar patterns (e.g.@: a proxy sharing network with a
service) and inter-container IPC without a shared daemon.

@section Sharing the Network Namespace

@option{--net container:@var{PID}} joins the network namespace of the
process with PID @var{PID}.  The container shares all network
interfaces, routing tables, and port bindings with that process.

@example
# Start the main container detached, capture its PID
./myapp --net none --detach
MAIN_PID=$!

# Sidecar joins the same network namespace
./sidecar --net container:$MAIN_PID
@end example

@section Sharing the IPC Namespace

@option{--ipc container:@var{PID}} joins the IPC namespace of the
process with PID @var{PID}.  Shared resources include:

@itemize
@item SysV semaphores (@code{semget}/@code{semop})
@item SysV message queues (@code{msgget}/@code{msgsnd}/@code{msgrcv})
@item SysV shared memory (@code{shmget}/@code{shmat})
@end itemize

@example
./service --ipc container:$MAIN_PID
@end example

@section Combining Both Flags

@example
./sidecar --net container:$MAIN_PID --ipc container:$MAIN_PID
@end example

@section POSIX Shared Memory

POSIX shared memory (@code{shm_open}, @file{/dev/shm}) lives in the
mount namespace and is not shared by @option{--ipc container:@var{PID}}.
To share it, bind-mount the same @file{/dev/shm} path into both
containers:

@example
./myapp    -v /dev/shm:/dev/shm
./sidecar  -v /dev/shm:/dev/shm
@end example

Or share the other container's @file{/dev/shm} directly:

@example
./sidecar -v /proc/$MAIN_PID/root/dev/shm:/dev/shm
@end example

@section Privilege Note

Joining a network or IPC namespace created by another container requires
that both containers were started by a process with matching user
namespace ownership, or that the joining process has root privileges.
If @code{setns(2)} fails, a descriptive error is printed and the
container exits.

