@node Networking Modes
@section Networking Modes

@opindex --net

@table @option
@item --net host
Share the host network stack (default).
@item --net none
Create an isolated network namespace with only a loopback interface.
@item --net container:@var{PID}
Join the network namespace of process @var{PID}.
@end table

@node Read-Only Rootfs
@section Read-Only Rootfs

@opindex --read-only
@cindex overlayfs

@option{--read-only} mounts the rootfs read-only via overlayfs.  Writes
go to a temporary upper layer discarded on exit; the on-disk rootfs is
never modified.  Falls back to read-write with a warning if overlayfs is
unavailable.

@example
./my-app --read-only
./my-app --read-only --tmpfs /tmp --tmpfs /var/run
@end example

@node Capabilities
@section Capabilities

@opindex --cap-drop
@opindex --cap-add
@cindex capabilities

@option{--cap-drop CAP} drops a capability from the bounding and
effective sets.  Pass @code{all} to drop every capability.
@option{--cap-add CAP} raises a capability as ambient so it survives
@code{exec(2)}.  Both are case-insensitive and the @code{CAP_} prefix is
optional.

@example
./my-app --cap-drop all
./my-app --cap-drop all --cap-add net_bind_service
./my-app --cap-drop net_raw --cap-drop sys_ptrace
@end example

@node Seccomp Filter
@section Seccomp Filter

@opindex --no-seccomp
@cindex seccomp

A default seccomp-BPF filter blocks syscalls with no legitimate use
inside a container:

@multitable @columnfractions .35 .65
@headitem Blocked syscall @tab Reason
@item @code{kexec_load}, @code{kexec_file_load} @tab Load a new kernel
@item @code{reboot} @tab Reboot the host
@item @code{syslog} @tab Kernel ring buffer access
@item @code{perf_event_open} @tab Used in kernel exploit chains
@item @code{bpf} @tab Load arbitrary BPF programs
@item @code{add_key}, @code{request_key}, @code{keyctl} @tab Kernel keyring manipulation
@item @code{userfaultfd} @tab Exploited in kernel escapes
@item @code{pivot_root} @tab Namespace escape vector
@item @code{ptrace} @tab Container escape
@item @code{process_vm_readv}, @code{process_vm_writev} @tab Cross-process memory access
@item @code{init_module}, @code{finit_module} @tab Kernel module loading
@end multitable

@code{PR_SET_NO_NEW_PRIVS} is always set.  To disable the filter:

@example
./my-app --no-seccomp
@end example

@node User Namespace
@section User Namespace

The loader always creates a user namespace (CLONE_NEWUSER) and maps the
host UID to UID@tie{}0 inside the container.  This makes the process
appear as root inside the container without granting real host
privileges.

