@node Subcommands
@chapter Subcommands

@menu
* inspect::
* list::
* prune::
* diff::
@end menu

@node inspect
@section inspect

@example
oci2bin inspect @var{BINARY}
@end example

Display OCI metadata embedded in @var{BINARY}: image name,
architecture, layer count, entrypoint, command, environment, working
directory, build digest, and build timestamp.

@node list
@section list

@example
oci2bin list [--json]
@end example

List all cached binaries with image name, digest, size, and build date.
@option{--json} emits machine-readable JSON.

@node prune
@section prune

@example
oci2bin prune [--dry-run]
@end example

Remove outdated cache entries, keeping only the most recently built
binary for each image name.  @option{--dry-run} shows what would be
deleted without deleting.

@node diff
@section diff

@example
oci2bin diff @var{OLD} @var{NEW}
@end example

Compare the filesystem contents of two oci2bin binaries.  Output lines
are prefixed with @code{+} (added), @code{-} (removed), or @code{M}
(modified).  Exits with status@tie{}0 if identical, or 1 if there are
differences.

@c ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
@node How It Works
@chapter How It Works

@cindex polyglot
@cindex ELF
@cindex tar archive

The output file is a polyglot: simultaneously a valid ELF64 executable
and a valid POSIX tar archive.

@example
Byte   0-3:   7f 45 4c 46   ELF magic  (kernel identifies as executable)
Byte 257-262: 75 73 74 61   ustar\0    (tar identifies as archive)
@end example

The 64-byte ELF header fits within the tar header's 100-byte filename
field.  When executed, the kernel processes the ELF; when passed to
@command{tar} or @command{docker load}, the tar structure is read.

@section File Layout

@example
[0-63]       ELF64 header  (embedded in the tar filename field)
[64-511]     Remaining tar header fields (ustar magic at byte 257)
[512-4095]   NUL padding   (page-aligns the loader for mmap)
[4096-~75K]  Loader binary (statically linked, gcc -static -O2 -s)
[~75K-end]   OCI image tar (manifest.json, config, layer tarballs)
@end example

@section Runtime Sequence

@enumerate
@item
Open @file{/proc/self/exe} and read the embedded OCI tar from the
patched offset.
@item
Extract image layers into a temporary rootfs under @file{/tmp} using
@command{tar --no-same-permissions --no-same-owner}.
@item
Patch @file{/etc/passwd} and @file{/etc/group} for single-UID namespace
compatibility (all UIDs/GIDs set to@tie{}0, except 65534).
@item
Enter a user namespace (@code{CLONE_NEWUSER}); map host UID to
container UID@tie{}0.
@item
Optionally join a shared network or IPC namespace via @code{setns(2)}.
@item
Enter mount, PID, and UTS namespaces.
@item
Apply volume bind mounts; optionally set up overlayfs.
@item
@code{chroot(2)} into the rootfs; mount @file{/proc}, @file{/tmp},
@file{/dev}.
@item
Apply seccomp filter, capabilities, UID drop.
@item
@code{exec(2)} the entrypoint.
@end enumerate

@section Security Properties

@itemize
@item
The process is unprivileged on the host; @code{CLONE_NEWUSER} does not
confer real root.
@item
Layer and config paths from the OCI manifest are validated against path
traversal.
@item
Volume container paths must be absolute and must not contain @code{..}.
@item
Tar extraction uses @option{--no-same-permissions --no-same-owner} to
prevent setuid bit restoration.
@item
Temporary directories are created with @code{mkdtemp} (mode
@code{0700}).
@end itemize

